On Zilliz Cloud, you store your vector embeddings in collections. All vector embeddings within a collection share the same dimensionality and distance metric for measuring similarity.
Zilliz Cloud collections support dynamic fields (i.e., fields not pre-defined in the schema) and automatic incrementation of primary keys.

To accommodate different preferences, Zilliz Cloud offers two methods for creating a collection. One provides a quick setup, while the other allows for detailed customization of the collection schema and index parameters.
Additionally, you can view, load, release, and drop a collection when necessary.
Against the backdrop of the great leap in the
industry, most developers just need a simple yet dynamic collection to start with. Zilliz Cloud allows a quick setup of such a collection with just three arguments:
Name of the collection to create,
Dimension of the vector embeddings to insert, and
Metric type used to measure similarities between vector embeddings.

from pymilvus import MilvusClient

# Replace CLUSTER_ENDPOINT and TOKEN with your own
client = MilvusClient(
    uri=CLUSTER_ENDPOINT, # Cluster endpoint obtained from the console
    token=TOKEN # An API key or a colon-separated cluster username and password
)

client.create_collection(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020",
    dimension=768,
    metric_type="COSINE"
)

client.get_load_status(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
)

# Output
#
The collection generated in the above code contains only two fields:
Enabling this setting ensures that the primary key increments automatically. There's no need for manual provision of primary keys during data insertion.

The automatically indexed and loaded collection from the provided code is ready for immediate data insertions.
Instead of letting Zilliz Cloud decide almost everything for your collection, you can determine the
of the collection on your own.
A schema defines the structure of a collection. Within the schema, you have the option to enable or disable
, add pre-defined fields, and set attributes for each field. For a detailed explanation of the concept and available data types, refer to

from pymilvus import DataType

# 1. Create the schema
schema = client.create_schema(
    enable_dynamic_field=True
)

# add the primary key
schema.add_field("id", DataType.INT64, is_primary=True, auto_id=True)

# add the vector field
schema.add_field("vector", DataType.FLOAT_VECTOR, dimension=768)

# add other scalar fields
schema.add_field("title", DataType.VARCHAR, max_length=512)
schema.add_field("link", DataType.VARCHAR, max_length=512)
schema.add_field("reading_time", DataType.INT64)
In the provided code snippet, the
is enabled for the primary key. Additionally, a
field is introduced, configured with a dimensionality of 768, along with the inclusion of four scalar fields, each with its respective attributes.
Index parameters dictate how Zilliz Cloud organizes your data within a collection. You can tailor the indexing process for specific fields by adjusting their
. On Zilliz Cloud, the recommended index type is always
. For the vector field, you have the flexibility to select
. For additional insights into index types, refer to

# 2. Set index parameters
index_params = client.prepare_index_params()

# Add an index on the vector field.
index_params.add_index(
    field_name="vector",
    metric_type="COSINE",
    index_type="AUTOINDEX"
)

# You can add indices on scalar fields too.
index_params.add_index(
    field_name="title",
    index_type="AUTOINDEX"

The code snippet above demonstrates how to set up index parameters for the vector field and a scalar field, respectively. For the vector field, set both the metric type and the index type. For a scalar field, set only the index type.
It is recommended to create an index for the vector field and any scalar fields that are frequently used for filtering.
You have the option to create a collection and an index file separately or to create a collection with the index loaded simultaneously upon creation.
Create a collection and an index file separately.

client.create_collection(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
    schema=schema
)

client.create_index(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020",
    index_params=index_params
)

res = client.get_load_status(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
)

# Output
#
The collection created above is not loaded automatically. For details, refer to
Create a collection with the index loaded simultaneously upon creation.

client.create_collection(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020",
    schema=schema,
    index_params=index_params
)

res = client.get_load_status(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
)

# Ouptut
#
The collection created above is loaded automatically. To learn more about loading and releasing a collection, refer to

During the loading process of a collection, Zilliz Cloud loads the collection's index file into memory. Conversely, when releasing a collection, Zilliz Cloud unloads the index file from memory.

client.load_collection(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
)

res = client.get_load_status(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
)

# Ouptut
#

client.release_collection(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
)

res = client.get_load_status(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020"
)

# Ouptut
#
If a collection is no longer needed, you can drop the collection.
For a serverless cluster, you can create up to two collections. For a dedicated cluster, the number of collections you can create varies with the CU that your cluster uses.
